Two things I tell my kids often:
✨I love you no matter what. I love you when you’re happy, I love you when you’re mad, I love you when you’re sad.
✨There’s nothing you’ll ever do to make me stop loving you.

With a 2 and a 4 year old, we get a lot of big feelings in our home. But I want my kids to know all feelings are welcome, no matter how big and scary, and they’re loved regardless. Even when those feelings lead to not so kind choices, they’re still loved.

I speak these words to them during hard moments and during calm moments. I hope they always know they’re always worthy of love and they will always have it from their parents. And it’s especially important in those times my emotions may escalate!

Would you? I want to hear your birth story! I really enjoyed my second birth and would totally live it again if I could! And people usually look at me like I’m nuts when I say that. I had a really different experience than the first time. Here’s a quick summary of Hudson’s birth:

Water broke at 1:30 am at exactly 38 weeks (I’d been 3.5cm with his head basically falling out at my appointment the day before, so I knew he’d come early but not that early)
Had no contractions but was told to go to the hospital. Had a pretty fast birth for a first time mom, so my 2nd was expected to go fast.
Wound up waiting around for hoursss for contractions to start and they didn’t
I was ready to have this baby so we decided on pitocin
Took awhile for things to kick in but my contractions finally hit around 11:30am and they hit HARD. 0-100 type of contractions.
Got an epidural about 7cm and decided to try to get some rest.
Not long after my midwife checked me and was like uh you’re having this baby right now! Jumped from a 7 to a 10 in like 30 mins.
Pushed for about 20 mins. She was like okay this kid should have been out after a few pushes he’s gotta be bigger than we expected.
I pushed on my side with my leg up and was able to watch the whole thing and feel his head which I thought was so cool!
He was born at 2:37pm at 8lbs 2.5oz with a hugee head. Much bigger baby than we thought
So when my labor finally kicked it, it was fast! Only 3 hours, just took awhile to get there.
I had a really good mental state with that birth. I was ready and excited and thankfully had no complications so I was able to really enjoy and experience it. It was such a special day and 100% would experience it again if I could.

No matter how you gave birth, natural, C-section, epidural, no epidural, home birth, hospital birth, whatever, you’re amazing! And trust me when I say I know I’m extremely fortunate to have had 2 healthy deliveries without complications. I know that’s not the case for every mama 🫶🏼

Do it scared. Making this as a reminder for myself but maybe it can help you too. Anxiety tries to hold me back from enjoying special moments. It gets in my head and tells me I can’t, that I’d be more comfortable at home, that it’s too hard. This weekend I said F U to anxiety. The day before my trip I had a really bad anxiety day. If you’ve been there, you know. The physical symptoms are awful. They’re debilitating. And your mind is just yelling run, run, run, no, no, no. I get bad anticipatory anxiety. I get anxious about getting anxious, so of course, I wind up anxious. It happened and I’m trying more and more not to fight it and just to ride it. That no matter what I was gonna sit through it and be there. The day before was bad, but I wound up having a great trip. Anxiety still crept in but it didn’t control my weekend. The only way to get over the anxiety is to get out of my comfort zone, as hard as it is. I’m so glad I did that and made core memories with my family.

So here’s my encouragement to you. If you have anxiety, no matter the reason or how it manifests, get out of your comfort zone. The only way to fight it is to meet it head on. Show yourself you can do it, even if you do it scared.

I’ve shared many times now I struggled with intrusive thoughts during pregnancy and postpartum with my first, but I struggled in silence when it was happening because I didn’t know it was a thing!! It was never on a postpartum questionnaire; my midwife never mentioned it. I truly thought I was going crazy and was worried if I said anything I’d be sent away or my baby would be taken.

I finally broke down to Ben after a few months and he looked it up for me. We learned together what it was but it still took me a LONG time to be open about it. 

If you’ve dealt with this or are currently I am here to tell you YOU ARE NOT ALONE. Don’t suffer in silence. If anything, I’m here for you. My DMs are always, always open. I wish future me could have given postpartum me a big fat hug and told me it was okay.

Hudson is 2.5 and I was so nervous about ditching the binky because he was obsessedddd. But it was time!

We’d been prepping him that the “binky fairy” would be coming soon and she’d turn his binkies into new toys. I was getting close to being ready to do it when he said himself he wanted to trade his binkies for toys, so we went with it that day!

Binkies went in the box, Hudson went down for a nap (and napped without a binky with 0 fuss!!) and after nap, the box was filled with a few toys for him and brother from the binky fairy!

And guess what, all that anxiety about ditching the binky was for nothing because he’s been GREAT!! He’s asked for it a handful of times, but we remind him where they went and that’s that. He’s had no trouble sleeping; it’s seriously been amazing and I couldn’t believe how easy it was. 

I think part of the success was the prep we did, part of it was him deciding the day to start and part was sheer luck.

This is something that has given me a lot of anxiety through most of motherhood. I’m outnumbered and so much can go wrong, but I realized I was depriving my kids and myself of experiences. It’s something I’ve really been working on the past few months and I learned, just like anything else, the more you practice, the more comfortable you become. The more you try, the more confidence you get in yourself and the more confidence you have in your kids.

What if it goes badly? It might. What if they’re crying? They might. What if people are judging you? They might. You might even wind up being the one crying. But that’s all okay! Really, it’s okay. But it also might go perfectly. And the more you do it the easier the challenging parts feel.

I feel like I’m on a journey to a new era of motherhood where I’m just allowing my kids to be kids and taking the pressure off myself to have them be perfectly behaved because it’s unrealistic.

And yes, it does get easier as the kids get older but I wish past me saw just how capable I was because it was possible then too.

Is this something that makes you anxious? I encourage you to try!

This is so simple and so many of you are going to be like duhhh but….

A night time reset (every night!)

I’ve consistently implemented this for a week now and wow actually kinda life changing for our home. If you’ve been around awhile, you’ll know I was actually pretty anti-reset. I valued my rest time and didn’t really care if I went to bed with a messy house because eh, I can clean it in the morning 🤷🏼‍♀️ except it would never get fully reset in the morning so I’d do big cleaning days on the days both boys were at school, which took up most of that free time.

Last weekend we had a party, so I had my home in a really clean place and I loved it. After the party I was determined to clean it back up and keep it that way, and I have.

Every night after the boys go to bed, I clear the floors, run the vacuum, clear and wipe tables and clean the kitchen. This small change has been huge. Turns out it’s so much easier to maintain a home doing this and reset nights aren’t nearly as timely as they used to be because it’s easier to maintain throughout the day now!
